  "response": "There are several highly regarded books for algorithms and data structures. Here are some top recommendations:\n\n1. Beginner Level:\n- \"Introduction to Algorithms\" by Cormen, Leiserson, Rivest, and Stein (CLRS)\n- \"Grokking Algorithms\" by Aditya Bhargava\n\n2. Intermediate Level:\n- \"Algorithms\" by Robert Sedgewick and Kevin Wayne\n- \"Data Structures and Algorithms in Python\" by Michael T. Goodrich\n- \"Cracking the Coding Interview\" by Gayle Laakmann McDowell\n\n3. Advanced Level:\n- \"Introduction to the Design and Analysis of Algorithms\" by Anany Levitin\n- \"Algorithm Design\" by Jon Kleinberg and \u00c9va Tardos\n\n4. Language-Specific:\n- Java: \"Data Structures and Algorithms in Java\" by Robert Lafore\n- C++: \"Data Structures and Algorithm Analysis in C++\" by Mark Allen Weiss\n- Python: \"Problem Solving with Algorithms and Data Structures\" by Bradley Miller\n\n5. Online Resources:\n- GeeksforGeeks\n- LeetCode\n- HackerRank\n\nThe \"best\" book depends on your programming background, learning style, and specific goals. CLRS is considered the most comprehensive, while Grokking Algorithms is more beginner-friendly.",
